docs.abstract: John Akomfrah’s films have shaken up official narratives around Black identity and imperialism. His latest tries to make sense of life in the pandemic.
docs.snippet: John Akomfrah’s films have shaken up official narratives around Black identity and imperialism. His latest tries to make sense of life in the pandemic.
docs.lead_paragraph: LONDON — Shortly before the artist and filmmaker John Akomfrah left Ghana for Britain after a 1966 coup, the nine-year-old-boy had a final encounter with his grandfather, the High Priest of the Akomfrah clan. The venerated old man wore a ring that had passed down through generations, representing the power to bring order to life’s chaos. It seemed like a perfect parting gift for his eldest grandson.

headline.main: An Artist Who Brings Order to Chaos

docs.abstract: A Black superintendent’s email to parents after the killing of George Floyd engulfed a small, predominantly white Maryland community in a yearlong firestorm.
docs.snippet: A Black superintendent’s email to parents after the killing of George Floyd engulfed a small, predominantly white Maryland community in a yearlong firestorm.
docs.lead_paragraph: CENTREVILLE, Md. — When Andrea Kane sat down to write a letter to parents in her school district days after George Floyd’s death in 2020, images of the Black man pleading for his life under the knee of a white Minnesota police officer were haunting her.

headline.main: Black Lives Matter, She Wrote. Then ‘Everything Just Imploded.’
headline.print_headline: After Note on Racism, School District ‘Imploded’

docs.abstract: Just weeks after another company was criticized for razing ancient caves in the Pilbara desert, BHP said it would expand an iron ore mine on land that contains rock shelters some 15,000 years old.
docs.snippet: Just weeks after another company was criticized for razing ancient caves in the Pilbara desert, BHP said it would expand an iron ore mine on land that contains rock shelters some 15,000 years old.
docs.lead_paragraph: MELBOURNE, Australia — A giant mining company on Thursday said it would go ahead with destroying at least 40 ancient Indigenous sites in the Pilbara desert in Western Australia, just days after a national outcry over revelations that other archaeological sites in the region had been razed.

headline.main: Mining Firm Plans to Destroy Indigenous Australian Sites, Despite Outcry
headline.print_headline: More Australian Indigenous Sites to Be Lost to Mining

docs.abstract: The producer Ray Angry and the visual artist Katherine McMahon lead a project that reimagines songs freely available for public use for the current moment.
docs.snippet: The producer Ray Angry and the visual artist Katherine McMahon lead a project that reimagines songs freely available for public use for the current moment.
docs.lead_paragraph: One Saturday in April, at a Manhattan recording studio strewn with antique lamps and masked technicians, the singer Liv Warfield’s face was clouded in concentration as she layered harmonies into the outro of a rousing soul number. She noodled for a while, trying to work out which notes to add next. “We might have to go to the rafters,” she concluded.

headline.main: Old Songs in the Public Domain Get Makeovers With a Purpose
headline.print_headline: Reviving Old Songs With Fresh Ideas

docs.abstract: The W.N.B.A. star took time away from basketball to help Irons overturn his conviction.
docs.snippet: The W.N.B.A. star took time away from basketball to help Irons overturn his conviction.
docs.lead_paragraph: Jonathan Irons, whose bid for freedom from a 50-year prison sentence was embraced and pushed by the W.N.B.A. star Maya Moore, walked out of a Missouri penitentiary on Wednesday, nearly four months after a judge overturned his conviction on charges of burglary and assault.

headline.main: Jonathan Irons, Helped by W.N.B.A. Star Maya Moore, Freed From Prison
headline.print_headline: He Walks Free After an Assist From a W.N.B.A. Star

docs.abstract: As allies abandon the president, his favorite network revives familiar villains for the Biden era. And the prospects for a Trump TV media venture are “greatly diminished.”
docs.snippet: As allies abandon the president, his favorite network revives familiar villains for the Biden era. And the prospects for a Trump TV media venture are “greatly diminished.”
docs.lead_paragraph: His president reeling, his cable network at a crossroads, Tucker Carlson began his show on Thursday night asking a question that has echoed for weeks among anchors and producers at Fox News: “What is life going to be like for us on Jan. 21?”

headline.main: As Trump Reels, Fox News Has a Message for Viewers: Stick With Us
headline.print_headline: ‘We’ve Got Nowhere to Go’: After Trump, Fox Sticks With Message, if Not Messenger

docs.snippet: But #disabledandcute influencers say the fashion industry has been slow to embrace them.
docs.lead_paragraph: I have always believed that fashion is the window to the soul. As a Black disabled woman with cerebral palsy, a neurological disorder that affects movement on the right side of my body, I have gone through what I call the stages of fashion grief.
